Modeling and prediction for movies

Load data

load("movies.Rdata")
movies <- na.omit(movies) # Remove the NA values from the dataset

Part 1: Data

The dataset consists of movie information taken from Rotten Tomatoes and IMBD. The dataset has a total of 651 randomly samples movies produced and released before 2016. for each movie, 32 variables have been recorded. With this dataset, it is only possible to do an observational study, which can be generalized to movies produced and released before 2016.

Part 2: Research question

As a data scientist for the Paramount Pictures, i would like to investigate: How does genre affects the ratings and critic scores for a movie? Do the ratings given by critics coincide with ratings given by the audiences? For this i will be investigating the various genres among the data set, the IMDB rating, the critics score and audience score.

From the above data summary we can see that among all the genres the most common one is Drama with 305 movies out of 651 being of this genre. Comedy comes in second with 87 movies,which is much lower in number than that of Drama. The various ratings and scores indicate that the average score is generally between 55% to 65%. But while the lowest IMDB ratings and audience scores still fall around the 10% mark of the scoring system, the critic scores indicate a low rating of around 1% of the scoring system. This is a clear indication of critics scores being different from audience views. but among all the scoring systems, the highest scores still range between 90% - 100% of the scoring system, suggesting that perhaps the differences in the scoring between critics and audiences is more to do with how severely critics rate movies as compared to normal audiences.

Part 4: Modeling

Now we will begin modeling for the target response variable, which in this case is the movie ratings in terms of scores given. Since we have 3 rating systems, 2 from Rotten Tomatoes, distinguished by audience and critics scores, and one from IMDB which is the average ratings without distinguishing between audience and critics scores. Due to the clear normal distribution of the IMDB rating, and the fact that it has a high correlation factor with both of the other rating systems, we will use IMDB ratings as the target variable.

In this model, we will use the backward elimination mode i.e. start with all of the variables in the dataset and remove certain variables to create a parsimonious model.

The initial varibles will be: 1. Genre (genre) 2. Movie runtime in minutes (runtime) 3. MPAA rating of movie (mpaa_rating) 4. Month of theatre release (thtr_rel_month) 5. Have any of the main actors ever won an Oscar (best_actor_win) 6. Have any of the main actresses ever won an Oscar (best_actress_win) 7. Has the director ever won an Oscar (best_dir_win)

Now lets have a look at the initial model:

Inmodel <-lm(imdb_rating ~ genre+runtime+mpaa_rating+best_actor_win+best_actress_win+best_dir_win+critics_score+audience_score, data=movies)
summary(Inmodel)

Now lets perform the backward elimination method:

final_model <- step(Inmodel, direction = "backward", trace = FALSE)
summary(final_model)

The model now possess 4 variables, the Genre, the Run time, the Critics Score, and the Audience Score. The model also has a slightly larger adjusted r-squared value of 0.8157, hence obtaining almost the same variability with fewer variables from the dataset. Now lets generate an ANOVA for the final model:

anova(final_model)

We can see from the above tables that the variables in the final model are all statistically significant, hence we will reject the null hypothesis in favour of the alternative hypothesis that the coefficient of at least one of the variables is not 0. From the final model we can see that only 3 out of the 10 genres show statistical significance (p-value less than 0.05).Of these genres, Documentries and Mystery and Suspense have the highest coefficients of all the genres. The remaining significant variables: Run time, Critics Score and Audience Score are similar to genre in that all have a positive effect on movies ratings.

Now lets have a look at a histogram plot of the residual plots for the variables.

hist(final_model$residuals,ylab="Residuals",main="Histogram of Final model residuals")

We can see that the histogram is left-skewed. Now lets have a look at the Normal probability plot of the residuals.

qqnorm(final_model$residuals,main="Normal probability plot of the residuals")
qqline(final_model$residuals)

But the Normal probability plot of the residuals shows that the skewedness is towards the tail. Now lets look at the residuals vs fitted values plot to check the non-linearity, outlines, variances and any unequal errors.

plot(final_model$residuals~final_model$fitted,main="Residuals vs. fitted")
abline(0,0)

From the plot we can see that the residuals are homoskedastic, i.e the variance of the residual is constant. But there is the presence of outliers, mostly towards the lower half of the plot.

Part 5: Prediction

Now lets test the model to get a prediction the IMDB rating score for the 2016 historical action film, The Finest Hour staring Chris Pines, Casey affleck and Ben Foster. All variables obtained from IMDB and Rotten Tomatoes.

movie_2016 <- data.frame(genre = "Action & Adventure", runtime = 117, mpaa_rating = "PG-13",best_dir_win = "No" ,critics_score = 63, audience_score = 66)
predict(final_model,movie_2016)
##        1 
## 6.688788

From the model, the predicted IMDB rating score is 6.679 or 6.68, while the actual is 6.8, a discrepancy of about 0.12 points. Now lets look at the prediction interval:

predict(final_model,movie_2016, interval = "predict")
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 6.688788 5.761303 7.616273

This interval shows that the predictions could range from 5.76 to 7.6, a range of almost 1.84 points on the rating system. The actual IMDB rating falls within this interval. Lets look at another movie from 2016. La La Land is a Romantic Comedy musical film starring Emma Stone and Ryan Gosling. Again, all the variables have been taken from IMDB and Rotten Tomatoes.

movie_2016 <- data.frame(genre = "Musical & Performing Arts", runtime = 128, mpaa_rating = "PG-13",best_dir_win = "Yes" ,critics_score = 91, audience_score = 81)
predict(final_model,movie_2016)
##        1 
## 7.554998

The predicted rating is 7.55, while the actual is 8.0, a discrepancy of 0.45 points. The prediction interval for this movie is:

predict(final_model,movie_2016, interval = "predict")
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 7.554998 6.597358 8.512638

So the predicted rating score could range from 6.6 to 8.5, which is inclusive of the actual IMDB rating of 8.0. The upper and lower values in each predicted interval indicate the 95% Confidence interval (CI). In both cases the predicted and actual value fall within the 95% CI. Hence we can be 95% confident in the accuracy of the predicted IMDB rating.

Part 6: Conclusion

From the data we can conclude on the research question. The genre of a movie greatly effects the expectations of the movie and hence the Critics and Audience scores and ratings as well. Also Critics scores and Audience scores generally do seem to coincide with up to about a 10% difference. This difference may be due to personal preference or the strictness with which Critics analyse films as compared to common audiences. The generation of the various models in this project provided the tools to come up with a prediction model for the popularity of a movie to some extent. This prediction used IMDB rating scores as it target variable. But the prediction capability of the model is limited. As seen above, there are discrepancies between the predicted and actual IMDB scores of the 2 movies tested. In order to improve the prediction capability of the models, several steps can be taken: 1. Movies can be stratified by genre and the IMDB ratings, Critics scores and audience scores for each genre can be accurately analysed to obtain the true statistical variability in each genre. Seperate models for each genre can also be created and used in combination with a more general model to obtain more accurate predicted rating scores. 2. A larger dataset may be used to improve on variability of data. 3. Identify and utilize other characteristic data of movies such as: number of sequels, based on a popular book series or not, if the actors or director has ever been Nominated for an Oscar, how long the movie ran in theaters etc.
